titlestmt.titleproper: Guide to the Yale Course Lectures Collection
titlestmt.author: compiled by Daniel Hartwig

publicationstmt.publisher: Yale University. Department of Manuscripts and Archives

profiledesc.creation: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace on Thursday April 18, 2019 at 07:50

repository.corpname: Yale University. Department of Manuscripts and Archives

did.abstract: The collection consist of notes on course lectures taken by Yale students.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Forms part of Yale Record Group 47 (YRG 47), Collections documenting teaching and learning in Yale academic programs.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The materials are open for research. Portions of the collection cannot be duplicated due to fragility of materials. See collection contents for details.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Yale Course Lectures Collection (RU 159). Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Yale University records are arranged and described at the accession level by the creating office. The University Archives creates collection level descriptive records, but typically does no further arrangement and description at the accession level.

altformavail.head: Existence and Location of Copies
altformavail.p: Notes of Laurence Hewes on Josiah W. Gibbs's lectures are available on microfilm (70 frames on 1 reel, 35mm.) from Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library, at cost. Order no. HM114. Notes on Dr. Eli Ives's and Dr. William Tully's lectures are available on microfilm (1404 frames on 3 reels, 35mm.) from Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library, at cost. Order no. HM165.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection consist of notes on course lectures taken by Yale students.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The records are arranged by accession.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy for their personal use should consult Copying Services information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.
